Okay, I hung up the new hive box during the day. This is how it looks in the garden.
But let's take a moment to look back. "What's inside?" seems no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fish-eye lens camera, and also an infrared LED light I took off from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an odd shape because the side panels of the nest box can rotate. I bought it like that, and couldn't modify it, so I had to design it according to this configuration.
Since there is no power supply in the garden, the whole device is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 lithium battery.
I didn't take a photo of the battery or the charger, but this is the photo of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
After being fully charged, it can run for about 4 hours.
I call this feature "special function." In this way, the birds also have a bit of private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was good enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn definitely wouldn't work.
But the new access points have perfect coverage.
Now, I was even planning to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof, pointing downward toward the garden.
If I want to build more nest boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do it this way. Especially in places farther away from the house, I might need it.
